User survey for ImagingSociety 2025 - National MRI research infrastructure in Norway

Author

Dr. Athanasia M. Mowinckel

Published

September 20, 2025

Background

This report presents an analysis of the survey data collected for the national grant scheme application for MRI research infrastructure in Norway. The survey was designed to gather insights from the research community on the current use, needs, and challenges related to MRI for human research.

The following sections will present a summary of the key findings, including graphical representations of the quantitative data and a textual summary of the open-ended responses, with the help of the Gemini LMM.

Survey Results

Of the 41 responses, 15 participants reported they currently use MRI for research, 37% indicate a future interest in using the new MRI facility for their work.

Participant Demographics

This section provides an overview of the survey participants’ roles and institutions.

Research Areas

The survey respondents represent a diverse range of research areas, with a strong emphasis on cognitive neuroscience and related fields. Here’s a breakdown of the key themes:

  • Cognitive Neuroscience: This is the most prominent theme, with many respondents explicitly stating their involvement in cognitive neuroscience.
  • Neuroscience & Neurology: A broad category encompassing various neurological conditions (Multiple Sclerosis, Neurodegenerative diseases, Brain Injury) and brain-related research.
  • Mental Health: A significant focus on mental disorders, psychotherapy, child and adolescent psychiatry, mood disorders, and anorexia nervosa.
  • Aging & Dementia: Research related to healthy aging, dementia, and cognitive decline is a recurring theme.
  • Specific Cognitive Functions: Focus on attention, decision-making, learning, speech and language processing, music cognition, and bilingualism.
  • Medical Imaging & Data Analysis: A number of respondents indicated research interests in areas where medical imaging and data analysis are used.
  • Other areas of interest: Also include areas like Sexual Health, Women’s health, Rehabilitation, Clinical psychology and Paleoclimatology.

How MRI Would Enhance Research

Based on the survey responses, expanded access to MRI would significantly improve and expand research in several key areas:

  • Neurological and Psychiatric Disorders: MRI is crucial for understanding brain changes and function in conditions like ADHD (particularly in women), Alzheimer’s, Lewy body dementia, multiple sclerosis (MS), lupus nephritis, and other psychiatric disorders. It would allow for the identification of biomarkers, improved diagnostics, and the development of individualized treatment approaches.
  • Cognitive and Emotional Processes: Access to MRI would enable the study of the cerebral correlates of cognitive and emotional processes, memory, bilingualism, aging, and the impact of interventions on these processes.
  • Sexual Function and Behavior: Researchers would be able to investigate the neural mechanisms underlying normal and deviant sexual arousal, sexual decision-making, partner attraction, and sexual preferences.
  • Brain Stimulation and Plasticity: MRI would enhance the understanding of how non-invasive brain stimulation works and its potential as a treatment for clinical disorders. It would also allow for measuring the effects of interventions on brain anatomy, plasticity, and activity.
  • Impact of Hormones: Researchers can study how hormones impact the brain, including the impact of menopause and hormonal replacement therapy.
  • Multicenter Studies and Larger Sample Sizes: Improved MRI access would facilitate participation in multicenter studies, allowing for larger, more robust datasets and better collaboration across institutions, particularly in remote areas.
  • Basic Neuroscience Research: Respondents mentioned using or wanting to use MRI to investigate fundamental brain networks involved in cognition and to examine brain structure/function relationships.
  • Method Development: Improved access would allow the development of novel MRI sequences and algorithms for clinical applications.
  • Access for Research Participants: Some researchers noted that their participants may need access to MRI imaging as a result of their work.
  • Career Advancement: Some stated that expanded access would allow them to gather experience, and the data required to obtain external funding and advance their careers.
  • Geohazard Identification: One researcher mentioned a novel application of MRI for “diagnosing” geohazards in geological archives.
  • Interaction with Artificial Intelligence: Some researchers mentioned using MRI to study brain activity associated with human interaction with artificial agents.
  • Pain and Treatment: Improved access would allow researchers to study the relationship between brain structure/function, pain, and pain treatment.

The main obstacles that were highlighted that would be addressed are: access to MRI slots, lack of neuroradiologists, monetary expenses, difficult organization of studies.

In summary, increased MRI access is seen as essential for a wide range of research areas, enabling more detailed investigations of brain structure, function, and connectivity, ultimately leading to better understanding and treatment of neurological, psychiatric, and other health conditions.

Future Needs

This section analyzes which conditions are considered most important for the future of MRI research in Norway.

Summary of Free-text Comments

This section provides a summary of the open-ended comments, generated using the Gemini LMM.

Survey respondents highlighted the need for enhanced MRI research infrastructure, particularly outside of hospital settings and closer to university campuses like Bergen. A key suggestion was prioritizing research use of existing scanners over clinical applications, possibly through adjusted pricing models. Furthermore, there was strong support for fostering a collaborative MRI research community, specifically mentioning a desire for such a network in Tromsø. The existing scanner upgrades at the Institute for Veterinary Science were also noted as a relevant context.

Conclusion

The results of this survey paint a clear and compelling picture: there is a significant and unmet need for dedicated research-focused MRI scanners in Norway. Researchers across various disciplines, from psychology and linguistics to neurology and medicine, have voiced the critical role MRI plays in their work and the challenges they face due to limited access and resources. The reported difficulties in securing scanner time, the lack of dedicated neuroradiologists for research-specific image evaluation, and the instances of researchers being forced to conduct studies outside of Norway highlight a systemic bottleneck that is hindering the advancement of crucial research. Furthermore, the expressed desire for a more collaborative MRI research community and advanced analysis capabilities underscores the potential for a more strategically invested and supported infrastructure to foster innovation and accelerate discovery. Investing in dedicated research MRI scanners is not simply about acquiring new equipment; it is about empowering Norwegian researchers to remain competitive on the global stage, fostering cutting-edge discoveries, and ultimately, improving the health and well-being of the Norwegian population through advanced medical understanding and treatment. The time to address this critical need is now.
